segments.text: to know that I could do a day's work.
And when I say a day's work, it would be from sun to sun.
And I'd get a big dollar for it.
Just one dollar?
Just one dollar.
And that bought your school clothes?
And that helped to buy my school clothes.
And I was so proud of you.
Yeah.
I was proud to know that I could be of help to my family.
The question I must ask is, you've taught school for so long, and education has been at the center of your family and at the center of your life, because I saw you teach today.
I know you've been retired for a long time, but you had those kids blooming, just blooming with discovery.
In just one hour, they were discovering reading, they were discovering history.
And, you know, I think about the kids in Harlem and Watts and just the kids in Las Cruces, New Mexico, and I just think that

You know, to teach them the way you teach, to give them this value, I mean, if you could say something to every school child in this country, I bet you could say it and get it across and change their life.
What do you think?
Well, I know one thing.
Uh-huh.
You just stop, and it's an old saying, a spoonful of sugar...
makes the medicine go down.
A little boy that couldn't write his name today.
And I said, Johnny, sure you can.
Now you watch exactly what I do, Johnny.
You watch my hand.
Start right here.
It takes time.
It takes love and patience.
And I just said, watch it.
And he watched.
And I went up real slow.
Now lots of children's concept is quicker and they grasp it.
But others are slow.
So I took it very slow with Johnny.
And I took two letters at a time until I had written Johnny.
And then he came along and made his first two letters.
And I said, oh, that is so good.
But he just beamed.
He just blossomed.
I said, you did a good job, Johnny.
That's good.
And then he made eight with the two letters.
And then he came back and made two more.
And I showed you.
I did it step by step.
I think what is wrong...
where it is true we're living in a fast age and times change.
But patience and a desire to learn and a desire for a teacher to put it over and the love she has for that child can't be wiped out.
They have to admit
of all their educated philosophies that they stick at you, they can't wipe that out.
You have to love.
You have to love.
You have to have the patience.
You have to have that push and desire to open the door or the channel or the eyes of a child that can't see it.
Yes, that's right.
Indeed.
And when I opened the door to this little boy.
Today.
Today.
That is where I lit my candle today.
The good book tells you, if you can light one candle, how much it means.
Well, I lit my candle today.
Then the little boy over here, that I asked him what reading was.
Yeah.
And he come down with the little girl that was in the fifth.
She'll be in the fifth grade next year.
She's in the fourth now.
She couldn't tell me what reading was.
She didn't know.
Yet she'd sat here and heard all of this discussion.
And he came down with his fist, and he says, it's talk written down on paper.
That was great.
And it just thrilled me to death.
And he said, you don't read like that.
I was trying to break the habit of saying, A, this is a tree.
This is the ball.
And I was trying to get it over.
And that we had commas was just like a yellow light.
It's a signal light to slow.
That's good.
And that was what I was trying.
And who, what, when, where are all question words.
And you ask it like one.
You remember him picking that out?
I do.
And he said, can this one too?
I said, yes, it sure is.
So it opened the door.
It's just like throwing out a fishing line with a good bait on it.
You'll get a bite.
If the bait is good.
If the bait is not, it'll stay there and some will come along and nibble and off it'll go.
But if that bait's good, it's gone.
All right.
I threw that line out and he grabbed it right quick with that reading.
He understood.
You did.
It was great.
I want to ask you a question.
Since you grew up with that kind of value towards education and then, again, this was before you went to college to be a teacher that you believed in teaching like this.
I can see that.
Yes.
Yes, I did.
Because you learned and grew this way.
And I just want to come right out and ask you, do you think this had an influence on your cousin?
I know it was.
We grew up the same thing.
And Uncle Sam was one of the best teachers that ever walked in Blanco County.
Now, there's so much of this stuff that I hear.
Oh, his mother was an educator.
They never say an educator.
An educator.
They forget that Sam Johnson was one of the smartest, quickest-minded men that ever walked.
Now, Aunt Rebecca was good, I grant you.
She was smart in her way, but not an overall educated person.
Now, I'll take up for her anywhere.
She was a wonderful woman.
She had a great influence on me, and she had a great influence on Linda, and all the children she touched.
But when it come down to the fundamental facts, none of them could touch Uncle Sam.
Now, Kitty Clyde's mother was a teacher.
We grew up with teachers.
This community was teachers, teachers, teachers.
It believes in education.
To me, this is one of the greatest hearts of education.
Right here in the country.
All right.
You just take this old school right up here.
I can show you there's more people that's come out of the Johnson City School that have doctorate degrees than you'll find in any...
Well, that's a Class B school, and we didn't have any affiliation until 1948.
That's the truth.
And we've got plenty of people that came out with doctorate degrees.
Dr. Emmett Redford today, down there at the University of Texas.
Or Dr. James Dollyhike, down at...
No, at A&M.
A&M, Dolly Height, yeah.
Yeah, Dolly Height at A&M.
All right.
Neve Clark, Dr. Neve Clark down at A&M.
Oh, I could...
There's just a...
Cox, what's his name?
Sid.
Sid Cox.
Yeah.
I'm going to tell you.
He was quite a guy, yeah.
Well, he was a folklorist.
And I'll tell you, they lost the pattern when they made him.
But they didn't, they didn't, he was smart.
He had lots of brains, lots of brains.
But these people came out of this small town that people pass through every day.
That's right.
And I think that the people of Johnson City, I think that part of that reaching out and that value and that touching each other has been education.
I think so too.
I think so because we wanted to show people that we were something and we would make something out of this life, that we could do it.
I've got to ask you, when Lyndon began his education policies, you believe it was coming from this as well as from the political necessity of the country.
I do know it.
And he says that ignorance is our only enemy.
And that is right.
It really is our own enemy.
And we...
don't want to cultivate it, so let's kill it.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, I would attribute that, again, this is part of the people.
That's right.
That was in him.
And I won't tell you.
I think people need to know that.
And I think another thing, of course, they give them a bedtime.
I know they do.
But about...
all of this program of feeding the children and Head Start and all of that.
But let me tell you right now, that all stems from home.
What would a kid do?
He does well to get up and catch a bus and come in.
What if he had to do like Linda and the rest of us, ride five miles to school and get here by 8.30 these cold mornings?
And open eight gates.
I want to tell you right now, you'd either learn your horse to jump them or you'd learn to ride up and get them open.
Your hands are cold, your feet are cold, and you ride and you hook your bridle reins over the horn of the saddle and you put your hands in your pocket and make the old horse slow.
Well, do you think that?
And when we started, he had learned enough German, and we went to work down on the ranch and had those little Mexicans, and we got the German and the Spanish mixed up.
Nobody could understand us.
Speaking German, Spanish, neither.
And Papa spent half the time going to school to get us straightened out.
That's the truth for a while.
And I think that lemon, all of this had an effect on lemon.
Okay.
So you believe in his heart that one of the attributes of the Johnson family, and I will give this as a whole, it's not singled out.
It's no person's idea.
But as a whole, you do believe that it was part of the family structure.
I do believe it.
I believe it with everything in my soul and body.
We were brought up to be educated.
Let me tell you, there were nine children in my Grandpa Johnson's family.
Every one of those nine children could do something.
They were educated to do something.
Now, Aunt Mary was a great, great seamstress.
In those days, to be a seamstress, that was something.
That was.
All right.
And...
Aunt Lucy taught piano.
Aunt Frank was an artist.
She did some of the most beautiful work that you ever looked at.
Uncle George was a teacher.
Aunt Jess was a teacher.
Aunt Ava was a teacher.
Aunt Kate was a teacher.
My daddy did not teach school.
But there's not anybody that won't tell you in this county that my daddy was one of the best judges of livestock
of anybody that ever was.
He was good, and he was one of the most wonderful ropers that ever...
He served in political, or in cattle office.
What was he now?
He was cattle inspector, tick inspector for years.
Right, yeah.
All in South Texas and all through here.
All through that region, yeah.
And he also got the first right-of-ways for the Pertinolis Electric Co-op that was gotten to put up the lines because people were afraid of electricity.
And my daddy went out and talked to them.
They had faith in him.
They knew that he was an honest, hard-working man.
He was not a politician.
He was a home man.
And they had faith in him.
And he got the right-of-ways for the first...
Electric lights that came into Johnson City.
A monument.
And that was in what year?
The first electricity.
Back in 30... 35?
About 35.
About 35.
What was the first electric light in Johnson City to be lit up?
It was a little bitty... Oh, TPNL came in here.
TPNL.
TPNL.
Texas Power and Light with a little dynamo.
Oh.
And put it up over there.
And every church had its own little light plant.
Oh, I love that.

the school had their own little light they'd heavy you could burn a 15 watt light bulb in your room but not anymore because it wouldn't carry it yeah texas parent life just couldn't carry it right amazing that's just oh i don't know it's over there where the old soul house stands an old hen building really yeah how about that it sure was
Yeah, but I really believed.
Then when you look back, and then on my mother's side, all of them, well, my uncle was, Uncle Jay was, worked in a tax collector's office.
He's a deputy sheriff here for years and years, and worked in the- Well, that's Jay Johnson.
Jay Chapman.
Jay Chapman.
Uh-huh.
Aunt Mabel was a teacher.
Uh-huh.
My mother, so what could you expect?
Teachers everywhere.
Everywhere.
Everywhere.
Yeah, this community, yeah.
And we just, we knew nothing but to study and to work.
So that realization that ignorance is our worst enemy.
That's right.
Is true to heart, because when you were enlightened, I'm sure, by all of these teachers.
Every time you turned around, if you used the wrong word, they called you down, if it wasn't for everyone.
Yeah.
Of course, they don't do that now.
They say it embarrasses children.
But again, this isn't the sophisticated professorial community where the old professor takes the book off the shelf.
This was a whole unity group of people who simply valued knowledge.
That's right.
And do you know in the place of, we would get a little old current event paper every week.
Yeah.
But when we were young, I mean, we were in the seventh and eighth grade.
Uncle Sam was, of course, in the House of Representatives and things, and he would come back and he'd throw out questions.
We'd meet up there to play.
Maybe we wanted to play bingo or not bingo, croquenole or hearts or something, some kind of game.
Well, in place of getting to play, he'd give us...
topics to discuss.
And what do you think about ownership, government ownership of railroads?
Do you think that they should own our railroads and tell us how much they're going to charge us for hauling?
All right, you take the affirmative and you take the negative.
He would use the power of debate, right?
Right from the word go.
And he'd set us over here in a room, all right?
There'd be two of us over there and he'd come over here.
Well, what do you think about the League of Nations?
Yeah.
What do you think that we should be doing?
You take the affirmative and you take the negative.
You go in that room.
All right.
What do you think about Eugene V. Debs, who's come out on the Socialist Party?
What do you think the socialists have rights in this United States?
What are they going to do?
What's it good for?
Question, all right?
You take the affirmative.
You take the negative and get going.
You go up here and you pick out.
I don't care.
You can take out seniors and ask them things today in our government.
They can't tell you.
And say, now, you tell me what you think.
I'll give you five minutes to get up here and get this written.
Knowledge.
Knowledge.
Knowledge of everything that's happening in your world was of importance to you?
It was at that time.
We listened.
Even the young?
Little folks were seen and not heard.
We listened to what was going on.
We had to.
And if you didn't know it, you was called a dumb bunny.
So we just, that's the way we just lived.
That's the only entertainment we had.
That's all we had to do.
Was learning.
Was learning.
Yeah.
And he was poked down us three times a day.
Sure.
And in between meals.
Right.
It was really right.
Yeah, I think so.
It's not here today.
No.
You know, there's that big movement to go back to basics.
But I'm wondering if anybody really knows what the definition of basics are anymore.
I don't think so.
I don't think so.
That bothers me because... No, honey, when they tell you that 10 is as far as you need to count, you just as well forget it.
Right.
If you meet a certain quota of knowledge by a certain grade level, then you're okay, rather than to promote.
the expertise in any area.
There you are.
It's a crying shame.
It's worse than that.
Oh, it is.
But, I said before, we're following the footsteps of the Roman Empire.
Just exactly like they did.
We will fall flat on our face.
All but there.
We're all but fallen.
We're all but fallen.
We're all but there.
Yes.
It's really a shame.
God.
So what do you think people have to offer their children in the future?
What are they going to offer them?
What will they be to offer?
The child gets everything that he has a desire for.
Yeah.
Without
Any compensation at all?
Of what he needs.
Of what he needs.
Yeah, that's it.
I'm scared.
I want.
They wake up in the morning, I want.
They go to bed at night, I want.
I never will forget saying my prayer one night and asking God,
It was getting close to Christmas time, and old times were hard, and I knew it.
We were having a hard time on the ranch, and I said, I do hope that you make room for Santa Claus to come to our house, and he won't forget where we live.
That we live so far back down on the river, and he could get lost.
I can remember just saying that.
But please, God, ask him to bring me just one little doll that's not homemade.
Uh-huh.
You wanted to have...
I wanted a little doll that wasn't homemade.
Uh-huh.
Ten years old had never had a doll that wasn't homemade.
Yeah.
And tell me that... Uh-huh.
We were not poor.
We had everything.
I had everything.
I had all the love in the world.
I was the richest one going.
But earthly things were few and full.
The material.
The material.
We're a material nation now.
I mean, we really are.
Everything that we do is based on what we own and how much more we can get.
The material things were not there.
And I will forget Uncle Clarence went to town, and he bought all the little girls a doll and put them on the Christmas tree.
But to get this little doll, we each had to say a speech.
And then, or we had to do a dance, or we had to sing a song.
So again, you had to...
Show your own.
Own ability to do.
And you didn't.
And it wasn't hanging to you on a silver platter.
You earned it.
And what I'm trying to, the point I'm trying to make, what we did, we worked for.
Now, whether we could say a good speech or whether we could sing a good song or whether we could do a good dance, we got up and tried.
And we earned that ball for what we had done.
Well, let me ask you another question because you're a woman.
You're a woman in Texas.
Do you feel that you were ever put down or put in your place as you were growing up in your home?
Or that you were told that you had to be something and you couldn't be something else?
Or how were you raised?
I was told that a lady's place
was number one.
OK. B, quiet, polite, courteous.
You're big enough to?
You wanted to.
You could do it.
All I had to do was say, I can do it.
And I did it.
So as far as equal rights in your household, it was definitely there.
Right.
Always.
Because there's always a job to do.
I have always had all the power that I ever wanted, because I knew what I could do.
And I darn sure wasn't going to overjump it, because the more responsibility I took, the more I was going to have to take.
Yeah.
And I went, as Ivy Dildine said, I went just so far
Now, I didn't go any further.
Yeah.
And I tell you, I didn't.
You know that.
I know that, right.
I'd come in from work, work all day like a trooper, and then work at the house.
I'd do a day's work and a half a day after I got in from work.
Uh-huh.
And then go to the ranch and feed and check on the cattle and everything.
Uh-huh.
That's enough.
I knew when I had enough.
And I said, you can't do it.
A question, because I myself grew up with the hard lot, you might say.
But I ask that a woman's day-to-day, if she's a career woman, is a job from 8 to 5, let's say.
Well, sure, and we come in and we open up a pizza or we go to get a frozen dinner and stick it in the thing.
That's...
That's the way of life.
Do you think that women are being cheated today because of what's happened, that they don't see their ancestry?
I do.
More than anything in this world.
And let me tell you one thing.
They don't know their own strength.
They don't know what they could do if they would try.
Now, I work with girls up at the old ranch.
Yes, for the National Park Service.
That's right.
They're on a Monday.
I'll guarantee you at 80 years of age, I can work circles around every one of them.
Right.
And never know I've done it.
Yes.
I'm tired.
I'm tired.
Yeah.
There are muscles in their body that haven't ever been stretched.
That's right.
Yeah.
That's true.
It is, I'm sure.
And they don't.
But people in other countries, and I have to ask this on a country and a basic culture question.
People in foreign countries live with less luxury than we do.
Yes, much less luxury than we do.
Are they better off than we are, do you think?
Physically, yes.
Physically, yes.
Of course, some of them die young.
But it's their fault.
And when I say it's their fault, they just fail to take the precaution and listen to what their body tells them.
Well, I mean, your body's been through quite a bit itself, which I know.
Certainly.
I mean, you've lost several children in pregnancy because of the RH factor, which they didn't know about.
Heavens knew nothing about it.
Right, but here your own grandson, your great-grandchild, your daughter-in-law went out and had an injection, and now she can, you know, she went through her pregnancy fine, so...
Yeah, but that I didn't know.
They didn't have it, right.
Back in the 40s.
So you had the grief.
Yes, I did.
And it's something you don't overcome.
If I had a girl today, well, things would be different.
It still hurts.
You wish you'd had a daughter.
More than anything.
I know, I can see it.
But I have a son.
that takes the place of everybody and everything.
That he does.
He is the best thing in this world to me.
And I love him.
And I know I love him too dear.
Yes.
Because I know that.
But that's all I have.
Is one child.
I know.
One child, no sisters, no brothers.
I have nobody.
I know.
But I just hope God takes me before I have to give him up.
I think God's taking care of both of you right now.
On equal grounds.
Well, I'm sure that's right because we're both on borrowed time and we both know it.
But I don't even stop to think about it.
Because when my work's done and I'm through, my time will be up and I'll know it.
But right now, I've got plenty to do.
That's true.
I'm going to stop.
